You can configure your beans so that they are *closed* by the context, when the context is closing. When `context.close` is called, the context will close/(call the destroy method) on all the beans this context created.

Usual ways are to configure close-able beans with XML are to declare the destroy-method, as in:

    &lt;bean id=&quot;..&quot; destroy-method=&quot;close&quot; &gt;..&lt;/bean&gt;

or to let the bean implement the `DisposableBean` interface as in:

    public class MyBean implements DisposableBean {
      @Override
      public void destroy() throws Exception {
        System.out.println(&quot;destroy: called&quot;);
      }
    }

---
See also the (official) guide [Spring Shutdown Callbacks][1]


  [1]: https://www.baeldung.com/spring-shutdown-callbacks

If you are using Java 7 or later version then you can declare your context initialisation inside try with resources, so that you don&#39;t need to close context manually: 

    try(final AbstractApplicationContext applicationContext = new ClassPathXmlApplicationContext(filename))
    {
         //write your code
    } catch(Exception e){}

Also, In a non-web application environment, you register a shutdown hook with the JVM. Doing so ensures a graceful shutdown and calls the relevant destroy methods on your singleton beans so that all resources are released. Of course, you must still configure and implement these destroy callbacks correctly.

To register a shutdown hook, you call the registerShutdownHook() method that is declared on the AbstractApplicationContext class:

  

    public static void main(final String[] args) throws Exception {
      AbstractApplicationContext ctx
          = new ClassPathXmlApplicationContext(new String []{&quot;beans.xml&quot;});

      // add a shutdown hook for the above context... 
      ctx.registerShutdownHook();

      // app runs here...

      // main method exits, hook is called prior to the app shutting down... }
**And Spring&#39;s web-based ApplicationContext implementations already have code in place to handle shutting down the Spring IoC container gracefully when the relevant web application is being shutdown.**

 [source: spring-framework-reference][1]


  [1]: https://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/3.2.x/spring-framework-reference/html/beans.html

